{"title_page": "2022 United States Senate election in Wisconsin", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2022 United States Senate election in Wisconsin\n| country            = Wisconsin\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = yes\n| previous_election  = 2016 United States Senate election in Wisconsin\n| previous_year      = 2016\n| next_election      = 2028 United States Senate election in Wisconsin\n| next_year          = 2028\n| election_date      = November 8, 2022\n| image1             = \n| nominee1           = \n| party1             = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1      = \n| percentage1        = \n| image2             = \n| nominee2           = \n| party2             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2      = \n| percentage2        = \n| map_image          = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = County results\n| title              = U.S. senator\n| before_election    = [[Ron Johnson (Wisconsin politician)|Ron Johnson]]\n| before_party       = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election     = \n| after_party        = \n}}\n{{ElectionsWI}}\n\nThe '''2022 United States Senate election in Wisconsin''' will be held on November 8, 2022, to elect a member of the [[United States Senate]] to represent the [[Wisconsin|State of Wisconsin]].\n\nIncumbent two-term [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] U.S. senator [[Ron Johnson (Wisconsin politician)|Ron Johnson]] is eligible to seek a third term, but he has announced that he would retire.<ref name=\"jcarney1\">{{cite news |last1=Carney |first1=Jordain |title=Ron Johnson pledges to retire after serving one more Senate term |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/senate-races/300251-ron-johnson-will-retire-after-second-term |work=The Hill |date=October 10, 2016 |accessdate=November 10, 2016}}</ref> However, In 2019, he said that he would not rule anything out about either running for a third term or instead run for [[2022 Wisconsin gubernatorial election|Governor]].<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |date=May 18, 2019 |title=Sen. Ron Johnson not ruling out 2022 run for governor |url=https://www.wbay.com/content/news/Sen-Ron-Johnson--510118081.html |publisher=WBAY-TV |location=Green Bay, Wisconsin |accessdate=May 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Republican primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Potential====\n* [[Sean Duffy]], former Congressman \n*David Beth, [[Kenosha County, Wisconsin|Kenosha County]] sheriff<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schenek |first1=Dan |title=Kenosha County Sheriff David Beth says he may run for Ron Johnson's U.S. Senate seat in 5 years |url=http://www.wtmj.com/news/kenosha-county-sheriff-david-beth-says-he-may-run-for-wisconsins-us-senate-seat |publisher=Radio 620 WTMJ |date=March 17, 2017 |accessdate=March 21, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Ron Johnson (Wisconsin politician)|Ron Johnson]], incumbent U.S. senator<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |date=May 18, 2019 |title=Sen. Ron Johnson not ruling out 2022 run for governor |url=https://www.wbay.com/content/news/Sen-Ron-Johnson--510118081.html |publisher=WBAY-TV |location=Green Bay, Wisconsin |accessdate=May 18, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Mike Gallagher (American politician)|Mike Gallagher]], US Representative \n*[[Glenn Grothman]], US Representative \n*[[Tommy Thompson]], Former Governor and [[Secretary of Health and Human Services]], 2012 Senate nominee\n\n====Declined====\n*[[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]], former [[Governor of Wisconsin]]<ref>{{Cite news |date=July 18, 2019 |url=https://madison.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/scott-walker-takes-new-job-says-he-won-t-run/article_0b5d0ea7-2284-594b-8f61-79d3035ef966.html |title=Scott Walker takes new job, says he won't run for office in 2022 |author=Kelly Meyerhofer |newspaper=Wisconsin State Journal}}</ref>\n\n==Democratic primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Potential====\n*[[Russ Feingold]], former U.S Senator \n*[[Mandela Barnes]], Lieutenant Governor\n*[[Tony Evers]], Governor\n*[[Ron Kind]], US Representative \n*[[Gwen Moore]], US Representative\n*[[Tom Barrett (Wisconsin politician)|Tom Barrett]], Mayor of Milwaukee \n*[[Lena Taylor]], State Senator \n*[[Josh Kaul]], [[Wisconsin Attorney General]]\n*[[Mark Pocan]], US Representative\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2022 United States elections}}\n\n[[Category:United States Senate elections in Wisconsin|2022]]\n[[Category:2022 United States Senate elections|Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:2022 Wisconsin elections|United States Senate]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2022 United States Senate election in Wisconsin\n| country            = Wisconsin\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = yes\n| previous_election  = 2016 United States Senate election in Wisconsin\n| previous_year      = 2016\n| next_election      = 2028 United States Senate election in Wisconsin\n| next_year          = 2028\n| election_date      = November 8, 2022\n| image1             = \n| nominee1           = \n| party1             = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1      = \n| percentage1        = \n| image2             = \n| nominee2           = \n| party2             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2      = \n| percentage2        = \n| map_image          = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = County results\n| title              = U.S. senator\n| before_election    = [[Ron Johnson (Wisconsin politician)|Ron Johnson]]\n| before_party       = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election     = \n| after_party        = \n}}\n{{ElectionsWI}}\n\nThe '''2022 United States Senate election in Wisconsin''' will be held on November 8, 2022, to elect a member of the [[United States Senate]] to represent the [[Wisconsin|State of Wisconsin]].\n\nIncumbent two-term [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] U.S. senator [[Ron Johnson (Wisconsin politician